<br>
Ther is no doubt that, when a kindness becomes expected and demanded, it sours the giving.  When I hand something from the bank hardwon through the efforts of friends and family, and someone calls it &quot;crap&quot;, it can really dishearten.  But who taught them that is the way it is?<br>
<br>
I still try, our charter mandates that I do.  For the obvious beggars,  I still offer to show them where they can hunt to earn their keep, and buff them if they go and do so.  Our charter does not mandate how I help, or how I prioritize when and who I help.   <br>
<br>
There ARE real and true newbies out there, although the rarest of spawns.  Tunare bless them.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   They still have that wide-eyed wonder at the scope and breadth of Norrath.   You won't find them near the bank in RV or FP, lifts in Kelethin, or gates in FP.   You won't see them in /shout, /ooc, or /auction.  In fact, if you don't bother looking for them, you won't hear anything from them at all.   They're too busy trying to kill rats, bats, spiders, and orcs with a tarnished or cracked weapon, and little or no armor.  They're too busy trying to save those cp's and sp's to buy that first piece of leather, banded, or improved robe.  They're trying desperately to find a group so they won't die so much, only to discover the group took the other newbie in full crafted with an exe axe.  They keep trying and dying, a lot of the time all alone.  If you do address them, they call you &quot;Lord&quot; or <br>
&quot;Lady&quot; with an obvious and real excitment at having met an Elder.  If you strip off some adds, throw a buff or a heal, or give them one less time to run desperately, hopelessly back to the guards, they say THANK YOU.  And you can almost hear the real gratitude in their voice.   They may timidly ask you if they can inspect you, and Oooo and Ahhh at your gear, but they're wondering how they can find marvelous treasures like these, not how they can get them for nothing.   IF you give them a piece of useful advice, they act as if you've handed them 100kpp.  Heck, an elder bothering to talk to them is treated as a gift in itself.  These are the true newbies.<br>
<br>
A lot of trends and events they have no control over, some occurring long before they came to Norrath, have caused them to enter a Norrath that has become very unfriendly to the TRUE newbie.  In many ways, life in Norrath is much harder for them because they have become such a rare breed.<br>
<br>
If some jerk hasn't convinced them to beg, they keep trying to do it the &quot;hard&quot; way.  Then they quietly camp their last time in Norrath without saying anything.  No whining, just quiet resignation that Norrath has nothing for them.<br>
<br>
We can change that.  But it will take as long as it took for the beggars and the ungrateful to become the norm.  Look for those true newbies.  Help them without convincing them that a kindness becomes a divine right.<br>
When you're playing a twinked alt, seek out a true newbie and make sure you invite them to group with you.  Teach them that being an &quot;elder&quot; is neither a free ride/handout, or an egotistical arsehole who talks down to them.  Teach them that the payment required for your kindness is passing that kindness on to someone someday when they are the elder.  Share freely the most precious treasures we greybeards have, a little bit of our time, and our knowledge of how Norrath works.  Once you've touched a real newbie in that way, the growth is geometric, as they pass on what they've learned from you to those a bit younger.  They may be the &quot;bottom of the food chain&quot;, but that's the foundation we all stand on.  And someday they will be you and me.<br>
Do you want these newbies to choose to stay, or the ungrateful ones we all complain about?  You just need to bother to look for them in the first place.  <br>
<br>
Verant has always been wrong.  It really isn't their world, it's always been ours.  And the only real dynamic change we can make in Norrath is how we touch those who share Norrath with us.  In that way, each and every one of us really can change the face of Norrath.  It only takes a bit of your time.<br>
<br>
Gregar Mataennoo<br>
Ridgerunner<br>
Ranger 54<br>
